Wine Quality Dataset¶

In this homework we are working on the Wine Quality dataset, downloaded from the UCI repository. Authors: P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis.

The dataset actually contains two datasets corresponding to the two variants of red and white wine of the Portuguese "Vinho Verde". We will working on the red wine dataset since the limit of examples for the assessment is set to 5000.

The red wines dataset contains 12 features from which 11 are the chemical properties of the wine and the remaining is the quality awarded by an expert taster. The aim of this notebook thus is to train a model that predicts the quality of a red wine and, as we'll see then, deal with the unbalancing of the number of examples per class.

The number of examples is not uniformly distributed among the 6 classes of quality. This means that an hypothetical predicting model would generalize correctly most of the examples (that is, the normal wines, those whose label corresponds to quality 7, 6 and 5), but worse the minority ones, those whose quality is either excellent (that is, 8) or poor (that is, 4 or 3).

Skewness and kurtosis¶

Let's check the shape of the distributions of probability of every feature.

In [9]:
df.hist(bins=25,figsize=(9,9))
Out[9]:

       [<Axes: title={'center': 'total sulfur dioxide'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'density'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'pH'}>],
       [<Axes: title={'center': 'sulphates'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'alcohol'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'quality'}>]], dtype=object)

Let's calculate skewness ($s$). Its interpretation is:

  • $s > 0$ means asymmetric or biased to the right or positive
  • $s = 0$ means symmetric or unbiased
  • $s < 0$ mean asymmetric or biased to the left or negative

Bulmer (1979) proposed the following rule of thumb:

  • $s < |0.5|$ is a small skewness
  • $0.5 \leq |s| \leq 1.0$ is a moderate skewness
  • $|s| \gt 1$ is heavily skewness
In [10]:

Let's calculate kurtosis ($k$) according to Fisher's definition of Pandas library. Its interpretation is:

  • $k < 0$ (platykurtic) means less sharpness (apuntamiento) than normal distribution
  • $k = 0$ (mesokurtic) means same sharpness than normal distribution
  • $k > 0$ (leptokurtic) means more sharpness than normal distribution
In [11]:
df.kurtosis().sort_values(ascending=False) # Fisher's kurtosis
Out[11]:

citric acid             -0.788998
dtype: float64

Almost all features are right (positively) skewed, asymmetrics and leptokurtics.

  • Since the data is right skewed, it means that is has a higher number of data points (or examples) having low values. So when we train the model on this training data, it will perform better at predicting the quality of wines with low values compared to those with higher feature values. Skewness also tells us about the direction of outliers: most of outliers are present on the right side of the distribution.

  • Since the distributions are leptokurtics, it means that the model will predict better the values at the center than those at the tails. Kurtosis tells us about the frequency of outliers: the features with the most amount of outliers are chlorides, residual sugar and sulphates.

Correlation among features¶

Let's measure the correlation among each pair of features on a heat map

In [12]:
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(8,8)})
sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, fmt='.2f', linewidth=2, annot_kws={'fontsize':10})
Out[12]:
<Axes: >

It's proved that features with high correlation are more linearly dependant and hence have almost the same effect on the dependent variable (that feature we want to predict). So when two features have high correlation (positively or negatively), we can drop one of the two features. In this way the dataset becomes lighter. In our dataset there are no pair of features enoughly correlated so discarding a feature would not affect to the goodness of the prediction.

Partial conclusion¶

The accuracy is stuck at roughly 67 %. Tuning the hyperparameter doesn't help to increase the accuracy and drive into underfitting or overfitting models. Thus it doesn't depend on the classifier but on the dataset itself: the unbalancing of the dataset we show before on the skewed distributions for each feature. There aren't much enough examples to generalize correctly the accuracy over the minority examples. And the training processes deal minority examples like outliers, that is, tricky to classify properly.

A good way to deal with our unbalanced dataset consists of applying some resampling or over-sampling techniques, as we are going to see onwards.

Over-sampling technique: SMOT¶

Brief theoretical explanation¶

The supervised synthetic minority oversampling technique (SMOTE) consists of synthesizing (or populate artificially) elements for the minority class, based on those that already exist. It works randomly picking a point from the minority class and computing the k-nearest neighbors for this point. The synthetic points are added between the chosen point and its neighbors.

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/code/rafjaa/resampling-strategies-for-imbalanced-datasets

To implement SMOTE on our dataset we have used the module SMOTE of the library imblearn.over_samples (https://imbalanced-learn.org/stable/references/generated/imblearn.over_sampling.SMOTE.html).

In [27]:
my_nearest_neighbors = NearestNeighbors(n_jobs=8) # desirable more than one core to speed up the over-sampling process
smote = SMOTE(sampling_strategy='not majority', k_neighbors=my_nearest_neighbors) # important the str 'not majority'
X_smote, y_smote = smote.fit_resample(examples, labels) # returns a Pandas.DataFrame object

We desire to transform leptokurtic distributions into platykurtic ones or, ideally, into uniform distributions. Now we must populate the minority classes and to not allow SMOTE object to populate any of the majority classes. We get this by using the string 'not majority' as value of the parameter sampling_strategy.

Model selection: stratified shuffle split¶

We split the dataset into training and test set by using the stratified, shuffle, then splitting strategy in order to conserve the same number of examples per class in both sets.

    y_train = y_smote.iloc[train_index]

Summary and conclusions¶

In this notebook we have used the Wine Quality dataset to study the behaviour of an unbalanced dataset on final accuracy. We have plotted the frequency distributions of all features and we have measured the skewness and kurtosis of all of them. We have learned that the skewness indicates the direction of the outliers, and kurtosis talks about the number of outliers. Then we trained three different classifiers and it turned out the accuracy was stucked at roughly 67 %.

To solve the situation, we used SMOTE technique, which uses k-nearest neighbors algorithm, to populate only those under-represented classes in the dataset. The result was a new dataset having all classes equally and uniformly represented. We re-train out set of classifiers and we obtained better accuracies on the balanced dataset.
